export default "<!-- target: uk | interface: en | version: 1 -->\n<!-- Ukrainian. Extra chapters: seven cases + vocative (кличний), verb aspect (imperfective vs perfective), verbs of motion (іти/ходити + prefixes), synthetic future (читатиму), double negation + genitive of negation, conditionals with би/б. -->\n\n# The Ukrainian Alphabet <!-- slug: alphabet -->\n\nUkrainian is written in **Cyrillic** — 33 letters. The alphabet itself takes a few days to learn; pronunciation is mostly regular after that.\n\n## Letters unique to Ukrainian (vs Russian)\n\nThese four letters exist in Ukrainian but not Russian — they mark the language:\n\n| Letter | Name | Sound | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **і** | і | \"ee\" as in *bee* | місто (misto) — city |\n| **ї** | ї | \"yee\" — i with a built-in y glide | їхати (yikhaty) — to travel |\n| **є** | є | \"yeh\" | єдиний (yedynyi) — only |\n| **ґ** | ґе | hard \"g\" (never a fricative) | ґанок (hanok) — porch |\n\nRussian uses и where Ukrainian uses и AND і depending on etymology. Ukrainian и is a shorter, more central sound than the Russian и.\n\n## The apostrophe (апостроф)\n\nUkrainian uses an apostrophe ' (not a letter — a separator) between certain consonants and я/є/ї/ю to signal the consonant does NOT palatalize: *м'ясо (myaso — meat), п'ять (pyat — five), комп'ютер (kompyuter — computer)*. Think of it as a hard sign that's typographically light.\n\n## Key sounds\n\n- **и** — between the \"i\" in *bit* and the \"u\" in *but*. Shorter and more central than any English vowel.\n- **х** — like the \"ch\" in Scottish *loch* or German *Bach*. Never \"ks\".\n- **г** — a voiced version of х, a voiced velar fricative. Not the hard \"g\" — that's **ґ**.\n- **ч** — \"ch\" as in *church*\n- **ш** — \"sh\" as in *shop*\n- **щ** — \"shch\", like *fresh cheese* said fast: *щастя (shchastya — happiness)*\n- **ж** — \"zh\", like the \"s\" in *measure*\n- **ц** — \"ts\" as in *cats*\n- **дж** — \"dj/j\" as in *judge*\n- Palatalization: many consonants before і, е, я, ю, є become \"soft\" (tongue touches palate). This is the main pronunciation challenge.\n- Stress is not marked in ordinary text and must be learned per word — this is the #1 difficulty.\n\n## Transliteration note\n\nThroughout this guide: Ukrainian word (*romanization — English meaning*). Stress is marked with an accent when shown.\n\n---\n\n# No Articles, No Present \"To Be\" <!-- slug: no-articles-no-be -->\n\nTwo things Ukrainian learners notice immediately — and both are features, not bugs.\n\n## No articles\n\nUkrainian has no *a, an, the* — none whatsoever. Context, word order, and demonstratives handle the job:\n\n- *Я бачу кішку.* (Ya bachu kishku.) — I see a cat / the cat.\n- *Ця кішка велика.* (Tsya kishka velyka.) — This cat is big.\n\nWhen you translate from English, simply drop the article. When you translate into English, context decides which article to use.\n\n## No present tense of \"to be\" (бути)\n\nIn the present tense, Ukrainian drops the copula entirely:\n\n| Ukrainian | Transliteration | English |\n|---|---|---|\n| Я студент. | Ya student. | I am a student. |\n| Він лікар. | Vin likar. | He is a doctor. |\n| Вона гарна. | Vona harna. | She is beautiful. |\n| Де книга? | De knyha? | Where is the book? |\n\n- The copula **є** (ye) exists — it appears in definitions and philosophical statements: *Мова є душею нації.* (Language is the soul of a nation.) In everyday speech, є is often dropped.\n- **бути** (buty) is fully conjugated in past and future: *був, була, було, були* (buv, bula, bulo, buly — was/were).\n- In past and future you must use it: *Я був вдома.* (I was home.) *Вона буде тут.* (She will be here.)\n\n✗ English trap: Don't try to insert an equivalent of \"am/is/are\" — the missing verb IS the correct form.\n\n---\n\n# Nouns, Gender & the Seven Cases <!-- slug: nouns-gender-cases -->\n\nThis is the structural heart of Ukrainian. Cases are not optional decoration — they replace prepositions and mark every grammatical relationship. Invest here and the rest of the language opens up.\n\n## Gender\n\nThree genders: **masculine, feminine, neuter**. Mostly predictable from the ending:\n\n| Ending | Gender | Example |\n|---|---|---|\n| consonant | masculine | брат (brat — brother), стіл (stil — table) |\n| -о, -е | neuter | вікно (vikno — window), поле (pole — field) |\n| -а, -я | usually feminine | жінка (zhinka — woman), земля (zemlya — earth) |\n| -ь (soft sign) | either (must learn) | ніч (nich — night, F); день (den — day, M) |\n\n## The Seven Cases\n\nUkrainian has **7 cases**. Each encodes a grammatical role. You need to know all of them — they appear constantly.\n\n**Core function summary:**\n\n| # | Case | Ukrainian name | Key question | Core use |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Nominative | Називний | Хто? Що? (Who? What?) | Subject of sentence |\n| 2 | Genitive | Родовий | Кого? Чого? (Of whom? Of what?) | Possession, absence, quantity, after many prepositions |\n| 3 | Dative | Давальний | Кому? Чому? (To whom? To what?) | Indirect object, beneficiary |\n| 4 | Accusative | Знахідний | Кого? Що? (Whom? What?) | Direct object |\n| 5 | Instrumental | Орудний | Ким? Чим? (With whom? With what?) | Means/instrument, accompaniment, after \"to be\" in predicate |\n| 6 | Locative | Місцевий | На/В кому/чому? (In/on whom/what?) | Location (always with a preposition) |\n| 7 | **Vocative** | **Кличний** | — (addressing someone) | **Direct address — unique and alive in Ukrainian** |\n\n## The Vocative (кличний відмінок) — a Ukrainian pride\n\nThe **vocative** is the case for direct address. English has no equivalent — you just use the name. Ukrainian has dedicated endings, and using them is considered elegant and educated. Dropping the vocative in formal or literary contexts sounds foreign.\n\n| Nominative | Vocative | Translation |\n|---|---|---|\n| мама (mama) | мамо (mamo) | Mom! |\n| Андрій (Andrii) | Андрію (Andriyu) | Andrii! |\n| Тарас (Taras) | Тарасе (Tarase) | Taras! |\n| пан (pan — sir) | пане (pane) | Sir! |\n| друг (druh — friend) | друже (druzhe) | Friend! |\n| Україна (Ukraina) | Україно (Ukraino) | Ukraine! (in poetry) |\n\nThis is why Shevchenko's poems say *Україно* — it's the vocative, not a typo.\n\n## Core noun endings — summary table (masculine, singular example: **брат** — brother)\n\n| Case | Ending example | Form | Meaning note |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Nominative | -Ø | брат | The brother (subject) |\n| Genitive | -а/-я | брата | Of the brother / no brother |\n| Dative | -у/-ю | брату | To the brother |\n| Accusative | = nom (inanimate) | брата | See the brother |\n| Instrumental | -ом/-ем | братом | With the brother |\n| Locative | -у/-і (with prep) | (у) брату | About the brother |\n| Vocative | -е/-у/-ю | брате | Brother! |\n\nFeminine example: **сестра** (sestra — sister)\n\n| Case | Form | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| Nominative | сестра | sister (subject) |\n| Genitive | сестри | of the sister |\n| Dative | сестрі | to the sister |\n| Accusative | сестру | see the sister |\n| Instrumental | сестрою | with the sister |\n| Locative | (на) сестрі | about the sister |\n| Vocative | сестро | Sister! |\n\n## Plurals\n\nMost plurals are formed by adding -и/-і (masculine/neuter), -и (feminine): *брати, вікна, сестри*. The case system applies equally to plurals — every case has a plural form too.\n\n## Animacy\n\nAnimate masculine nouns (people, animals) have Accusative = Genitive: *Я бачу брата.* (Ya bachu brata — I see the brother.) Inanimate: Accusative = Nominative: *Я бачу стіл.* (I see the table.)\n\n---\n\n# Pronouns <!-- slug: pronouns -->\n\n## Personal pronouns (declined)\n\nUkrainian personal pronouns decline through all seven cases. The nominative forms:\n\n| Person | Singular | Plural |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1st | я (ya — I) | ми (my — we) |\n| 2nd | ти (ty — you) | ви (vy — you pl./formal) |\n| 3rd m | він (vin — he) | вони (vony — they) |\n| 3rd f | вона (vona — she) | — |\n| 3rd n | воно (vono — it) | — |\n\n**ви** (vy) is the formal singular \"you\" — use it with strangers, elders, officials. **ти** (ty) is informal. Mixing these up is a social faux pas in the wrong direction.\n\nKey declined forms you'll encounter constantly:\n\n| Nominative | Genitive | Dative | Accusative | Instrumental |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| я | мене | мені | мене | мною |\n| ти | тебе | тобі | тебе | тобою |\n| він | його | йому | його | ним |\n| вона | її | їй | її | нею |\n| ми | нас | нам | нас | нами |\n| ви | вас | вам | вас | вами |\n| вони | їх | їм | їх | ними |\n\nAfter prepositions, 3rd-person pronouns add **н-**: *до нього (to him), у неї (at her place), з ними (with them)*.\n\n## Possessive pronouns (agree in gender/number/case)\n\n| English | M sg | F sg | N sg | Plural |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| my | мій | моя | моє | мої |\n| your (sg) | твій | твоя | твоє | твої |\n| his | його | його | його | його |\n| her | її | її | її | її |\n| our | наш | наша | наше | наші |\n| your (pl/formal) | ваш | ваша | ваше | ваші |\n| their | їхній | їхня | їхнє | їхні |\n\nPossessives agree with the noun they modify — not the owner: *моя книга (my book, F), мій брат (my brother, M), моє вікно (my window, N)*.\n\n---\n\n# Question Formation <!-- slug: question-formation -->\n\n## Three ways to ask a question\n\n**1. Intonation** — the easiest. Take a statement, raise your voice on the key word:\n*Ти знаєш Андрія?* (Ty znayesh Andriya?) — Do you know Andrii?\n\n**2. The particle ЧИ (chy)** — placed at the start, signals yes/no question. More formal, unambiguous:\n*Чи ти знаєш Андрія?* (Chy ty znayesh Andriya?) — Do you know Andrii?\n*Чи вона прийде?* (Chy vona pryde?) — Will she come?\n\n**3. Question words**\n\n| Word | Translit | English |\n|---|---|---|\n| хто? | khto? | who? |\n| що? | shcho? | what? |\n| де? | de? | where? (location) |\n| куди? | kudy? | where to? (direction) |\n| звідки? | zvidky? | where from? |\n| коли? | koly? | when? |\n| чому? | chomu? | why? |\n| як? | yak? | how? |\n| який? яка? яке? | yakyy? | which? / what kind? |\n| скільки? | skilky? | how many/much? |\n\nQuestion words go to the front: *Куди ти йдеш?* (Where are you going?) *Що це таке?* (What is this?)\n\n---\n\n# Verb Aspect — Imperfective vs Perfective <!-- slug: verb-aspect -->\n\nThis chapter is the most important in the guide. Ukrainian does not have \"tenses\" the way English does — it has **aspect**. Until you internalize aspect, you're translating from English grammar that doesn't exist in Ukrainian.\n\n## The core idea\n\nEvery Ukrainian verb exists in (at least) two forms:\n- **Imperfective (недоконаний вид)** — the action as an **ongoing process**, **repeated habit**, or **general fact**. It doesn't tell you whether the action was completed.\n- **Perfective (доконаний вид)** — the action as a **single completed event** with a **result**. It implies the action reached its goal.\n\n| English | Imperfective | Perfective |\n|---|---|---|\n| to write | писати (pysaty) | написати (napysaty) |\n| to read | читати (chytaty) | прочитати (prochytaty) |\n| to speak | говорити (hovoryty) | сказати (skazaty) |\n| to do/make | робити (robyty) | зробити (zrobyty) |\n| to buy | купувати (kupuvaty) | купити (kupyty) |\n| to come | приходити (prykhodуty) | прийти (pryyty) |\n\nTypically a prefix transforms imperfective → perfective: *писати → на**писати***. Or a different root: *говорити (say things generally) → сказати (say one specific thing)*.\n\n## What changes with aspect\n\n**1. Present tense**: ONLY imperfectives have a present tense. Perfectives do not — if you conjugate a perfective in \"present\" endings, it means FUTURE.\n\n**2. Past tense**: both aspects have past. The difference is narrative:\n- *Вчора я **читав** книгу.* (Vchora ya chytav knyhu.) — Yesterday I was reading a book. (process, maybe didn't finish)\n- *Вчора я **прочитав** книгу.* (Vchora ya prochytav knyhu.) — Yesterday I read (finished) the book.\n\n**3. Future tense**: imperfective future uses *буду + infinitive*; perfective future conjugates like a present verb (see Future chapter).\n\n## Choosing aspect in practice\n\n| Situation | Aspect | Example |\n|---|---|---|\n| Habit / repeated action | Imperfective | Я завжди **читаю** перед сном. (I always read before bed.) |\n| Action in progress | Imperfective | Вона зараз **читає**. (She's reading now.) |\n| General capability | Imperfective | Він добре **малює**. (He draws well.) |\n| Single completed event | Perfective | Я **прочитав** цю книгу. (I've read / I read this book — done.) |\n| Requesting a one-time action | Perfective | **Напиши** мені. (Write to me — once.) |\n| Requesting an ongoing/repeated action | Imperfective | **Пиши** мені частіше. (Write to me more often.) |\n\n✗ Trap: \"I read Ukrainian every day\" → imperfective: *Я читаю українською щодня.* NOT perfective.\n✓ \"I've read this article\" → perfective: *Я прочитав цю статтю.*\n\nMnemonic: perfective = **P**oint in time, **P**roduct/result. Imperfective = **I**nfinite process, **I**teration.\n\n---\n\n# Present Tense <!-- slug: present-tense -->\n\nOnly imperfective verbs have a true present tense. Two conjugation classes:\n\n## Class I — -е endings (most verbs)\n\n**читати (chytaty — to read)**\n\n| Person | Form | Translit |\n|---|---|---|\n| я (I) | читаю | chytayu |\n| ти (you sg) | читаєш | chytayesh |\n| він/вона/воно | читає | chytaye |\n| ми (we) | читаємо | chytayemo |\n| ви (you pl) | читаєте | chytayete |\n| вони (they) | читають | chytayut |\n\n## Class II — -и endings\n\n**говорити (hovoryty — to speak)**\n\n| Person | Form | Translit |\n|---|---|---|\n| я | говорю | hovoryu |\n| ти | говориш | hovorysh |\n| він/вона | говорить | hovoryt |\n| ми | говоримо | hovorymo |\n| ви | говорите | hovoryte |\n| вони | говорять | hovoryat |\n\nCommon irregular presents:\n- **бути (to be)**: є (ye) for all persons in affirmative (or omitted); **немає** (nemaye) = there is no\n- **їсти (to eat)**: їм, їси, їсть, їмо, їсте, їдять\n- **іти (to go on foot)**: іду, ідеш, іде, ідемо, ідете, ідуть\n- **хотіти (to want)**: хочу, хочеш, хоче, хочемо, хочете, хочуть\n- **дати (to give)**: дам, даси, дасть, дамо, дасте, дадуть\n\n---\n\n# Past Tense <!-- slug: past-tense -->\n\nThe Ukrainian past tense is built differently from any West European language — it **agrees with the subject in gender and number**, not in person. There is only one past form per gender/number.\n\n| Subject gender/number | Ending | Example (читати) | Translit |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Masculine singular | -в | читав | chytav |\n| Feminine singular | -ла | читала | chytala |\n| Neuter singular | -ло | читало | chytalo |\n| Plural (all genders) | -ли | читали | chytaly |\n\n*Він читав книгу.* (He was reading / read a book.)\n*Вона прочитала книгу.* (She read [finished] the book.)\n*Ми говорили годину.* (We spoke for an hour.)\n\nThis means the verb gives you information about the subject's gender — useful when the subject is implied.\n\n✗ Common mistake for English speakers: don't look for person agreement (no first/second/third distinction): *Я читав* (I read, masculine speaker) vs *Я читала* (I read, feminine speaker) — the verb changes with the speaker's gender.\n\nFor **бути**: *був (buv) / була (bula) / було (bulo) / були (buly)*.\n\n---\n\n# Future Tense <!-- slug: future-tense -->\n\nUkrainian has **two** future constructions, corresponding to the two aspects.\n\n## Imperfective future — буду + infinitive\n\nDescribes an ongoing or repeated action in the future. Uses *буду/будеш/буде/будемо/будете/будуть* + imperfective infinitive:\n\n*Я **буду читати** цей роман увесь тиждень.* — I will be reading this novel all week.\n*Ми **будемо говорити** про це завтра.* — We will be talking about this tomorrow.\n\n## Perfective future — synthetic (the distinctive form)\n\nDescribes a single completed future action. Formed by conjugating the perfective verb with the SAME endings as the present tense Class I or II — but it means future because perfectives have no present:\n\n**написати (napysaty — to write [perfective])**\n\n| Person | Form | Translit | English |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| я | напишу | napyshu | I will write |\n| ти | напишеш | napyshesh | you will write |\n| він/вона | напише | napyshe | he/she will write |\n| ми | напишемо | napyshemo | we will write |\n| ви | напишете | napyshete | you will write |\n| вони | напишуть | napyshut | they will write |\n\n*Я **напишу** тобі листа.* — I will write you a letter. (and I will finish it — result implied)\n*Вона **прочитає** звіт до п'ятниці.* — She will read (finish reading) the report by Friday.\n\nThe synthetic perfective future is one of Ukrainian's most distinctive features — there's nothing quite like it in English.\n\n---\n\n# Verbs of Motion <!-- slug: verbs-of-motion -->\n\nUkrainian distinguishes how you move, not just where. This matters for prefix combinations.\n\n## The key pairs\n\n| Meaning | Unidirectional (one trip) | Multidirectional (repeated/general) |\n|---|---|---|\n| to go on foot | іти (ity) | ходити (khodyty) |\n| to go by vehicle | їхати (yikhaty) | їздити (yizdyty) |\n| to fly | летіти (lteity) | літати (litaty) |\n| to swim/sail | плисти (plyty) | плавати (plavaty) |\n| to carry (on foot) | нести (nesty) | носити (nosyty) |\n| to carry (by vehicle) | везти (vezty) | возити (vozyty) |\n\n**іти** — I am walking to the store right now (one trip, in progress).\n**ходити** — I walk to work every day (general habit, repeated, or wander around).\n\n*Зараз я **іду** до магазину.* (I am going to the store now.)\n*Я **ходжу** до магазину щодня.* (I go to the store every day.)\n\n## Prefixes transform motion verbs\n\nAdding a prefix to the unidirectional form creates a perfective verb; adding it to the multidirectional creates an imperfective. Key prefixes:\n\n| Prefix | Meaning | Imperfective (multidirectional) | Perfective (unidirectional) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| при- | arrival | приходити (come [repeatedly]) | прийти (arrive) |\n| ви- | exit | виходити (go out [habit]) | вийти (go out [once]) |\n| за- | stopping by | заходити (stop by [habit]) | зайти (stop by [once]) |\n| пере- | crossing | переходити (cross [habit]) | перейти (cross [once]) |\n| від- | departure | відходити (leave [habit]) | відійти (leave [once]) |\n| про- | passing by | проходити (pass by [habit]) | пройти (pass by [once]) |\n\n*Він **зайшов** до кав'ярні.* (He stopped by the café — once, perfective.)\n*Він **заходить** до нас щонеділі.* (He stops by every Sunday — habit, imperfective.)\n\n---\n\n# Adjectives & Adverbs <!-- slug: adjectives-adverbs -->\n\n## Adjective agreement\n\nAdjectives agree with the noun they modify in **gender, number, and case** — all three simultaneously. This is the main complexity of Ukrainian adjectives.\n\nLong-form adjective endings (nominative):\n\n| Gender/Number | Ending | Example (новий — new) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Masculine singular | -ий / -ій | новий будинок (new building) |\n| Feminine singular | -а / -я | нова машина (new car) |\n| Neuter singular | -е / -є | нове місто (new city) |\n| Plural (all genders) | -і / -ї | нові книги (new books) |\n\nHard stems (-ий/-а/-е/-і), soft stems (-ій/-я/-є/-і).\n\n*великий (velykyi — big): великий стіл, велика кімната, велике вікно, великі міста*\n\nAdjectives follow the noun less often than in English — they usually precede.\n\n## Comparison\n\n- Comparative: adjective + **-іший / -ший**: *новіший (newer), більший (bigger from великий)*\n- Or: **більш** + adjective: *більш складний (more complex)*\n- Superlative: **най-** prefix: *найновіший (newest), найкращий (best)*\n- Irregular: *гарний (beautiful) → кращий (better-looking) → найкращий; поганий → гірший → найгірший*\n\n## Short-form (predicative) adjectives\n\nIn the predicate position after бути, some adjectives have short forms: *радий (glad), певний (sure), готовий (ready)*. These are used in fixed expressions.\n\n## Adverbs\n\nMost adverbs are formed from adjectives by replacing the ending with **-о**: *швидкий → швидко (quickly), добрий → добре (well/good), тихий → тихо (quietly)*.\n\nComparative adverb = comparative adjective (same form): *швидше (faster), краще (better), більше (more)*.\n\n---\n\n# Prepositions and the Cases They Govern <!-- slug: prepositions -->\n\nUkrainian prepositions are bound to specific cases — learning a preposition without its case is only half the information.\n\n## Genitive prepositions\n\n**до (to/until), від (from), без (without), для (for), після (after), під час (during), замість (instead of), крім (except), з/із (from, out of), біля (near), через (through/in [time])**\n\n*до магазину* (to the store) | *від Андрія* (from Andrii) | *без молока* (without milk) | *для мами* (for mom) | *після роботи* (after work) | *біля університету* (near the university)\n\n## Dative prepositions\n\n**по (along/around, after — colloquial), завдяки (thanks to), всупереч (contrary to)**\n\n*завдяки тобі* (thanks to you) | *по вулиці* (along the street)\n\n## Accusative prepositions\n\n**в/у (into, on — with motion), на (onto — with motion), за (behind/for — with motion), під (under — with motion), через (across, in [time]), про (about)**\n\n*у ліс* (into the forest) | *на стіл* (onto the table) | *через тиждень* (in a week) | *про це* (about this)\n\n## Instrumental prepositions\n\n**з/із (with — together), між (between), над (above), під (under — static), перед (in front of), за (behind — static)**\n\n*з другом* (with a friend) | *між будинками* (between the buildings) | *над містом* (above the city)\n\n## Locative prepositions (always required with this case)\n\n**в/у (in, at — static), на (on, at — static), при (at/by), по (after — formal)**\n\n*у місті* (in the city) | *на столі* (on the table) | *при університеті* (at the university)\n\n## Same preposition, different case, different meaning\n\n**у/в**: *іти **в** ліс* [accusative — into the forest] vs *бути **в** лісі* [locative — in the forest]\n**на**: *покласти **на** стіл* [accusative — onto the table] vs *лежати **на** столі* [locative — on the table]\n**під**: *поставити **під** стіл* [accusative — under the table] vs *стояти **під** столом* [instrumental — standing under the table]\n\nThis motion/location split is consistent throughout Ukrainian.\n\n---\n\n# Numbers & Case Agreement <!-- slug: numbers-cases -->\n\nNumbers in Ukrainian are grammatically demanding — they govern the noun's case differently depending on their value.\n\n## Cardinal numbers\n\n| Number | Ukrainian | Translit |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | один/одна/одне | odyn/odna/odne |\n| 2 | два/дві | dva/dvi |\n| 3 | три | try |\n| 4 | чотири | chotyry |\n| 5 | п'ять | pyat |\n| 10 | десять | desyat |\n| 100 | сто | sto |\n| 1000 | тисяча | tysyacha |\n\n## The case rules (the hard part)\n\n| Numeral | Case of following noun |\n|---|---|\n| 1 (один) | Nominative singular |\n| 2, 3, 4 (два, три, чотири) | Genitive singular |\n| 5–20, etc. | Genitive plural |\n| 21, 22, 23, 24 | Follow the last digit (so 21 → nom sg, 22 → gen sg) |\n\n*один студент* (one student, nom sg)\n*два студенти* (two students, gen sg)\n*п'ять студентів* (five students, gen pl)\n*двадцять один студент* (twenty-one students, nom sg — follows \"один\")\n\nWhen the whole noun phrase is NOT the subject, the number itself declines and takes the noun with it — this is advanced territory, but be aware cases apply to numerals too.\n\n## Ordinal numbers\n\nForm like adjectives and agree in gender/number/case:\n*перший/перша/перше* (first), *другий* (second), *третій* (third), *четвертий* (fourth), *п'ятий* (fifth)\n\n---\n\n# Negation <!-- slug: negation -->\n\n## Double negation — mandatory in Ukrainian\n\nUkrainian requires **double (or multiple) negation** — every negative element in the sentence takes negative form. This is not \"bad grammar\"; it is the rule.\n\n*Я нічого не знаю.* (Ya nichoho ne znayu.) — I don't know anything. (literally: I nothing-GEN NOT know)\n*Він нікуди не ходив.* (Vin nikudy ne khodyv.) — He didn't go anywhere. (literally: He nowhere NOT went)\n*Ніхто нічого не сказав.* (Nikhto nichoho ne skazav.) — Nobody said anything.\n\nNegative pronouns/adverbs:\n- **ніхто** (nobody), **ніщо/нічого** (nothing), **ніде** (nowhere — location), **нікуди** (nowhere — direction), **ніколи** (never), **ніяк** (no way)\n\nAll of these MUST co-occur with **не** before the verb.\n\n✗ English logic: \"I don't know anything\" → Ukrainian does NOT say *я не знаю щось* — that means something else.\n\n## Genitive of negation (родовий заперечення)\n\nWhen the verb is negated, the direct object often shifts from **Accusative** to **Genitive**:\n\n*Я маю **книгу**.* (I have a book — accusative.) → *Я не маю **книги**.* (I don't have a book — genitive.)\n*Він купив **хліб**.* (He bought bread — accusative.) → *Він не купив **хліба**.* (He didn't buy bread — genitive.)\n\nThis is not always obligatory (especially with specific/definite objects) but it's the dominant pattern.\n\n## Немає — the key negative existential\n\n**Немає** (nemaye) = there is no / there isn't:\n*Немає часу.* (There is no time. — genitive: *часу*)\n*Немає молока.* (There is no milk.)\n*Мене немає вдома.* (I'm not home. — genitive of pronoun: *мене*)\n\nThe opposite is **є** (there is/are) or simply stated without є.\n\n---\n\n# Conjunctions & Complex Sentences <!-- slug: conjunctions -->\n\n## Core conjunctions\n\n| Ukrainian | Translit | English | Type |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| і / й / та | i / y / ta | and | coordinating |\n| але / проте | ale / prote | but | coordinating |\n| або | abo | or | coordinating |\n| бо / тому що | bo / tomu shcho | because | subordinating |\n| хоча | khocha | although | subordinating |\n| якщо | yakshcho | if | subordinating |\n| коли | koly | when | subordinating |\n| що | shcho | that | subordinating |\n| щоб | shchob | so that / in order to | subordinating |\n| який/яка/яке | yakyy | which/that (relative) | relative |\n\n## що (that)\n\n**що** introduces content clauses — it is NOT optional, unlike English \"that\":\n*Я думаю, **що** він має рацію.* — I think (that) he is right.\n*Вона сказала, **що** прийде.* — She said (that) she would come.\n\n## щоб (so that / in order to)\n\n**щоб** introduces purpose clauses and reported commands. It triggers the **past tense** in the subordinate clause (a quasi-subjunctive):\n*Я прошу, **щоб** ти прийшов.* — I ask that you come / I want you to come.\n*Він поїхав, **щоб** побачити її.* — He left in order to see her.\n\n## який as a relative pronoun\n\n**який/яка/яке/які** agrees in gender/number with its antecedent and declines for case in its own clause:\n*Книга, **яку** я читаю, дуже цікава.* — The book (that) I'm reading is very interesting. (*яку* = accusative because it's the object of *читаю*)\n*Хлопець, **якому** я допоміг, — мій сусід.* — The boy whom I helped is my neighbor. (*якому* = dative)\n\n---\n\n# Conditionals — би/б <!-- slug: conditionals -->\n\nUkrainian conditionals are formed with the **particle би (by) or б (b)** — the choice is purely phonetic (б after vowels, би after consonants). This particle combines with the past tense form.\n\n## Real conditional (якщо… то)\n\nFor real/possible conditions, use **якщо (yakshcho — if)** + present/future:\n*Якщо буде сонце, ми підемо в парк.* — If it's sunny, we'll go to the park.\n*Якщо ти прийдеш, я буду рада.* — If you come, I'll be glad.\n\n## Unreal/hypothetical conditional (би + past)\n\nFor unreal or hypothetical situations (both present-unreal and past-unreal — same form in Ukrainian):\n**якби + past tense … би + past tense**\n\n*Якби я знав, я б сказав тобі.* (Yakby ya znav, ya b skazav tobi.) — If I knew / had known, I would have told you.\n*Якби вона прийшла, ми б поговорили.* — If she came / had come, we would have talked.\n\nNotice: Ukrainian uses the **same construction** for what English splits into second and third conditionals. The past tense in the subordinate clause signals unreality, not past time.\n\n**би/б** can appear in either or both clauses, and can be used without якби to express a polite wish:\n*Я б хотів каву.* (Ya b khotiv kavu.) — I would like a coffee.\n*Вона б поїхала в Київ.* — She would go to Kyiv.\n\n---\n\n# Imperatives <!-- slug: imperatives -->\n\n## Formation\n\n**Informal singular (ти)** — the base imperative:\n- Class I verbs: remove -є from 3rd sg present, add -й: *читає → читай (read!)*\n- Class II verbs: remove -ть from 3rd pl present, result is the stem: *говорять → говор- → говори (speak!)*; if stem ends in consonant cluster: *напишуть → напиш- → напиш!*\n\nCommon imperatives: *скажи (say!), іди (go!), дай (give!), будь (be!), дивись (look!), слухай (listen!), іди (go!), почекай (wait!)*\n\n**Formal/plural (ви)** — add **-те** to the singular form:\n*читайте, говоріть, скажіть, дайте, будьте*\n\n## Let's — first person plural imperative\n\nAdd **-мо** or **-ймо** to the stem:\n*Ходімо! (Khodimo!)* — Let's go!\n*Говоримо. / Говорімо.* — Let's talk.\n*Читаймо!* — Let's read!\n\n## Softening imperatives\n\nA bare imperative can sound rude. Add **будь ласка** (bud laska — please) or use the conditional to soften:\n*Дай мені, будь ласка, …* — Please give me …\n*Чи не міг би ти …?* — Could you possibly …?\n\n---\n\n# A Note on Ukrainian vs Russian <!-- slug: ukrainian-vs-russian -->\n\nThis note is for learners who approach Ukrainian knowing Russian — a common path.\n\n**Do not assume transfer.** Ukrainian and Russian share Cyrillic and some vocabulary, but are distinct languages with different grammars, sounds, and lexicons.\n\nKey structural differences:\n- Ukrainian has the **vocative case**; Russian dropped it.\n- Ukrainian has **і, ї, є, ґ**; Russian does not.\n- Ukrainian **г** is a voiced fricative (like an English \"h\" but voiced); Russian г is a stop \"g\".\n- Ukrainian keeps the **synthetic future** (*читатиму*); Russian uses only *буду читать*.\n- Ukrainian has **more aspect pairs with lexical differentiation** rather than just prefixation.\n- Many common words differ entirely: *говорити (Ukrainian) vs говорить (Russian — same); але (Ukrainian but) vs но (Russian but); та (Ukrainian and) — Russian rarely uses та*.\n- False friends: Ukrainian **рот** (rot — mouth) vs Russian *год* (god — year); Ukrainian **луна** (luna — echo) vs Russian *луна* (luna — moon — same!); Ukrainian **неділя** (nedilya — Sunday) vs Russian *неделя* (nedelya — week).\n\nIf you're coming FROM Russian: the vocabulary overlap will help, but fight the urge to russify Ukrainian phonology (especially г vs ґ, and и vs і).\n\n---\n\n# Describing a Movie <!-- slug: describing-a-movie -->\n\nPlot summary convention: use **present tense** (imperfective, ongoing) for narrating the story.\n\n**Opening:** *Це фільм про…* (Tse film pro… — This is a film about…) | *Фільм розповідає про…* (The film tells about…) | *Дія відбувається в…* (The action takes place in…)\n\n**Genre:** *комедія (comedy), трилер (thriller), драма (drama), бойовик (boyovik — action film), мелодрама (romance), фантастика (sci-fi), жах / фільм жахів (horror)*\n\n**Narrating plot (present tense, imperfective):**\n*Головний герой хоче…, але…* (The main character wants…, but…)\n*У фільмі розповідається про жінку, яка…* (The film tells about a woman who…)\n*Наприкінці…* (At the end…)\n\n**Opinion vocabulary:**\n- *Мені сподобався фільм.* (Meni spodobavsya film.) — I liked the film. (past perfective — single event of liking)\n- *Фільм дуже цікавий / нудний / зворушливий / захоплюючий.* (interesting / boring / touching / gripping)\n- *Гра акторів чудова.* (The acting is wonderful.)\n- *Сюжет (syuzhet — plot), кінець (kinets — ending), саундтрек (soundtrack), спецефекти (special effects)*\n- *Рекомендую подивитися.* (I recommend watching it.) — perfective, one-time action\n- *Не варто дивитися.* (Not worth watching.)\n\n**The -ий/-а trap in opinions:** Unlike English, the adjective ending changes with gender of the noun: *фільм цікавий* (M) but *книга цікава* (F) but *кіно цікаве* (N).\n";
